Bug report. An MCP server (stdio JSON-RPC on stdout) also starts an HTTP SSE server at boot. When the configured port is already in use, the WHOLE process exits/crashes instead of just failing to start SSE. We need the stdio MCP server to keep running even if SSE can't bind.

Here is the end of startSseServer():

```ts
export function startSseServer(taskStore: TaskStore): http.Server {
    const server = http.createServer((req, res) => { /* ... request handling ... */ });

    const SSE_PORT = parseInt(process.env["SSE_PORT"] ?? "3001", 10);
    const SSE_HOST = process.env["SSE_HOST"] ?? "127.0.0.1";
    server.listen(SSE_PORT, SSE_HOST, () => {
        logger.info({ host: SSE_HOST, port: SSE_PORT }, "SSE server listening");
    });

    return server;
}
```

Why does an in-use port crash the entire process, and how do you fix it so the process survives (SSE simply disabled) with an actionable log? Also note we'd like the port to be injectable for tests.

result:
ROOT CAUSE: The `server.listen()` call emits an `'error'` event when the port is in use, but no error handler is attached. Node.js crashes the process on unhandled server errors. The port is also hardcoded via environment variables, making tests difficult.

FIX:
```ts
export function startSseServer(taskStore: TaskStore, ssePort?: number, sseHost?: string): http.Server | null {
    const server = http.createServer((req, res) => { /* ... request handling ... */ });

    const SSE_PORT = ssePort ?? parseInt(process.env["SSE_PORT"] ?? "3001", 10);
    const SSE_HOST = sseHost ?? process.env["SSE_HOST"] ?? "127.0.0.1";

    server.on('error', (err: NodeJS.ErrnoException) => {
        if (err.code === 'EADDRINUSE') {
            logger.warn({ host: SSE_HOST, port: SSE_PORT, error: err.message }, 
                "SSE server failed to bind (port in use), continuing without SSE");
            return;
        }
        logger.error({ host: SSE_HOST, port: SSE_PORT, error: err.message }, 
            "SSE server error");
    });

    server.listen(SSE_PORT, SSE_HOST, () => {
        logger.info({ host: SSE_HOST, port: SSE_PORT }, "SSE server listening");
    });

    return server;
}
```

Update the call site to handle the nullable return and ignore SSE if unavailable:
```ts
